r felons, Native Americans, and others, Richard Hasen argues that American democracy can and should do better in assuring that all eligible voters can cast a meaningful vote that will be fairly counted. He shows how a constitutional right to vote can deescalate voting wars between political parties that lead to endless rounds of litigation and undermine voter confidence in elections, and can safeguard democracy against dangerous attempts at election subversion like the one we witnessed in the aftermath of the 2020 presidential election.The path to a constitutional amendment is undoubtedly hard, especially in these polarized times. A Real Right to Vote explains what’s in it for conservatives who have resisted voting reform and reveals how the pursuit of an amendment can yield tangible dividends for democracy long before ratification.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConstitutional amendmentszUnited States. 0aElection lawzUnited States. 0aSuffragezUnited States. 0aVoter suppressionzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Constitutions.2bisacsh  aA Real Right to Vote: How a Constitutional Amendment Can Safeguard American Democracy.  aFifteenth Amendment.  aNineteenth Amendment.  aPrinceton University Press.  aRichard L. Hasen.  aSupreme Court.  aTwenty-Sixth Amendment.  abooks: politics.  aconstitutional amendment.  aconstitutional law.  aelection law.  aelection subversion.  aelections.  aelectoral college.  afelon voting.  aright to vote.  aterritorial voting.  avoter suppression.  avoting rights.  avoting wars.  avoting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074975540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691257723?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691257723423Coveruhttps://www.d